  "articleSummary": "The article argues that the Single‑Responsibility Principle (SRP) is valuable when applied with judgment, but “Single‑Purpose People” misuse it by equating “small” with “cohesive,” leading to over‑fragmented codebases. It illustrates how obsessive line‑count rules and excessive modularisation—especially in React/Redux‑style architectures—produce file‑system sprawl, tangled dependencies, brittle tests, and slowed development velocity. The tone is a critical analysis mixed with a rant, using metaphors of “shrapnel,” “Rube Goldberg,” and “infinite work pattern” to frame the problem. The piece is aimed at software engineers, architects, and team leads who grapple with code organization and want pragmatic guidance on applying SRP at the right level of cohesion.",
